<dl id="n12114b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12114b">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12114b"> 114(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ask for child, get 5</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Waldel&egrave;ne, duc de la Bourgogne transjurane, vint ainsi le trouver, avec son &eacute;pouse Flavia. Pr&eacute;venus des faveurs de la fortune, ils se fussent estim&eacute;s au comble du bonheur, si un enfant avait souri &agrave; leur foyer; il ne leur restait qu&apos;un espoir: l&apos;intercession du saint abb&eacute;. &ldquo; Si vous consentez, leur r&eacute;pondit-il, &agrave; consacrer au Tr&egrave;s-Haut le don qu&apos;il vous fera, et &agrave; me choisir comme parrain de son / bapt&egrave;me, je veux bien demander &agrave; la divine cl&eacute;mence de vous accorder, non seulement cet enfant que vous lui offrirez en pr&eacute;mices, mais encore autant d&apos;autres que vous le souhaiterez.&rdquo; Ils souscrivirent de grand c&oelig;ur &agrave; cette condition et Flavia fut &agrave; peine rentr&eacute;e qu&apos;elle ressentit les premi&egrave;res joies de la maternit&eacute;. Waldel&egrave;ne n&apos;oublia point sa promesse; son fils fut baptis&eacute; &agrave; Luxeuil et recut le nom de Donat. Et Dieu ne se laissa pas vaincre en g&eacute;n&eacute;rosit&eacute;: un second fils naquit, puis deux filles, douce r&eacute;compense de cet abandon &agrave; la Providence <br><font color="green">[Waldelene, the Duke of Burgundy, came to see him with his wife Flavia. Overwhelmed with the gifts of fortune, they would have deemed themselves supremely happy if a child had been smiling in their home. One hope alone remained for them: the intercession of the holy abbot. &lsquo;If you agree&rsquo;, he told them, &lsquo;to dedicate to the Almighty the gift he would make for you and to choose me as the godfather at his baptism, I would then ask the Divine Benefactor to grant your wish, not only for the child that you would offer Him as first-fruits, but also whatever others you will desire&rsquo;. They agreed to this condition with pleasure and Flavia had scarcely returned when she felt the first stirrings of maternity. Waldelene did not forget his promise: his son was baptised at Luxeuil and received the name Donat. And God was not to be outdone in generosity: a second son was born, then two daughters, a sweet reward for this surrender to Providence.]</font> <small> <a name="STCM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#STCM"><cite title="source">Saint Colomban</cite></a> (1905) 65-6</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
